    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
        <body>
            <div rend="parallel">
                <p xml:id="KT386-kilavi">piriviṭai vaṟpuṟuttun tōḻikkuk kiḻatti vaṉpoṟaiyetir aḻintatu </p>


                <p xml:lang="en">Spoken when being desolate in the face of
                    encouragement by HER to the confidante, who encourages [her] in the time of
                    separation. </p>
            </div>

            <div rend="parallel">
                <lg xml:id="KT386">
                    <l> veṇmaṇal virinta vītatai kāṉaṟ</l>
                    <l> ṟaṇṇan tuṟaivaṉ ṟaṇavā vūṅkē</l>
                    <l> vāliḻai makaḷir viḻavaṇi kūṭṭu</l>
                    <l> mālaiyō vaṟivēṉ maṉṉē mālai</l>
                    <l> nilamparan taṉṉa puṉkaṇoṭum</l>
                    <l> pulampuṭait tākuta laṟiyēṉ yāṉē.</l>


                </lg>

                <lg xml:lang="en">
                    <l rend="indent"> Before <note place="foot">
                            <term xml:lang="ta">ūṅkē </term> here is one of the rare cases of
                        subordination marked with -ē, though here one can ask whether this is not
                        due to a kind of formulaic compulsion (negative absolutive + <term xml:lang="ta">ūṅkē</term> is found in four further cases in the KT
                        at the end of the poem).</note> the man from the cool ghat, by the seashore
                        grove</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> full of blossoms spread out in the white sand, departed,</l>
                    <l> as for evenings, <note place="foot">
                            <term xml:lang="ta">mālai-y-ō</term> is difficult, though it might be
                        explained as a case of demarcation of topic: "as for evenings ...".</note></l>
                    <l> when women with pure jewels put together festive ornaments,</l>
                    <l rend="indent6"> I would certainly know <note place="foot">
                            <term xml:lang="ta">aṟivēṉ</term> : the future has to be read as a kind
                        of habitual past here.</note> [them].</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> That <note place="foot">For the function of <term xml:lang="ta">ākutal</term> as a pointed "that" cf. KT 4.4, 360.2.</note>
                        evening possesses loneliness along with sorrow</l>
                    <l> as if to cover the [very] earth I didn't know.</l>


                </lg>
            </div>
        </body>
